In React lazy components are used to load components only when they are needed instead of loading them at the initial page load.
this technique is called lazy loading and help improve application performance and bundle size.

Why React.lazy is needed
By default, a React app bundles all components into a single JavaScript file.
As the app grows, this bundle becomes large, causing:
	• Slower initial page load
	• Higher memory usage
	• Poor performance on low-end devices
React.lazy solves this by dynamically importing components.

What React.lazy does
React.lazy allows you to:
	• Load a component on demand
	• Split your JavaScript bundle into smaller chunks
	• Reduce initial load time
It works together with Suspense to show a fallback UI while the component is loading.



import React, { Suspense } from "react";
const Dashboard = React.lazy(() => import("./Dashboard"));
function App() {
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>
      <Dashboard />
    </Suspense>
  );
}
export default App;

==================================================================================================================================
In React, **`React.lazy` by itself does NOT show a loader**.  
👉 **The loader is shown by `<Suspense fallback={...}>`**, *not* by `React.lazy`.

This is a very important concept and a common interview question.

***

## ✅ Correct Expectation (Key Rule)

> **Whenever you use `React.lazy`, you MUST wrap the lazy component with `<Suspense>` to show a loader.**

If you don’t:

*   ❌ Nothing renders
*   ❌ App may throw an error
*   ❌ No loader appears

***

## ✅ Basic Example: React.lazy with Loader

### 1️⃣ Lazy load the component

```tsx
import React, { lazy, Suspense } from "react";

const Dashboard = lazy(() => import("./Dashboard"));
```

***

### 2️⃣ Wrap with Suspense (WHERE loader is defined)

```tsx
function App() {
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>
      <Dashboard />
    </Suspense>
  );
}
```

✅ **`fallback` is the loader**  
✅ Shown while `Dashboard` JS bundle is loading

***

## ✅ What Happens Internally

    Render starts
     ↓
    React.lazy starts loading JS chunk
     ↓
    Suspense shows fallback (loader)
     ↓
    JS chunk fully loaded
     ↓
    Suspense removes fallback
     ↓
    Component renders

***

## ❌ WRONG: Using React.lazy Without Suspense

```tsx
const Dashboard = lazy(() => import("./Dashboard"));

function App() {
  return <Dashboard />; // ❌ ERROR
}
```

❌ React throws:

> “A component suspended while rendering, but no fallback UI was specified.”

***

## ✅ Loader Can Be Anything (Spinner, Skeleton, etc.)

```tsx
<Suspense fallback={<Spinner />}>
  <Dashboard />
</Suspense>
```

```tsx
<Suspense fallback={<Skeleton height={300} />}>
  <Profile />
</Suspense>
```

✅ Not just text

***

## ✅ Route-level Lazy Loading (Most Common in Real Apps)

### React Router Example

```tsx
import { Routes, Route } from "react-router-dom";
import { lazy, Suspense } from "react";

const Admin = lazy(() => import("./Admin"));

function AppRoutes() {
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<div>Loading page...</div>}>
      <Routes>
        <Route path="/admin" element={<Admin />} />
      </Routes>
    </Suspense>
  );
}
```

✅ Loader shows only when route is loading  
✅ Very common pattern

***

## ✅ Component-level Lazy Loading

```tsx
function Page() {
  const [show, setShow] = useState(false);

  return (
    <>
      <button onClick={() => setShow(true)}>Open</button>

      {show && (
        <Suspense fallback={<div>Loading modal...</div>}>
          <LazyModal />
        </Suspense>
      )}
    </>
  );
}
```

✅ Loader only when modal loads

***

## ✅ Custom Reusable Loader Wrapper (Best Practice)

```tsx
function LazyWrapper({ children }) {
  return <Suspense fallback={<Loader />}>{children}</Suspense>;
}
```

Usage:

```tsx
<LazyWrapper>
  <Dashboard />
</LazyWrapper>
```

✅ Clean  
✅ Reusable  
✅ Team-friendly

***

## ❓ Where Exactly Is Loader Displayed?

📌 **At the Suspense boundary location**

```tsx
<Suspense fallback={<Loader />}>
  <Component />   // loader replaces THIS area
</Suspense>
```

Not full page unless Suspense wraps full page.

***

## ⚠️ Important Gotchas

### ❌ React.lazy ≠ loader

```tsx
lazy(() => import("./Comp")); // ❌ no loader
```

### ✅ Suspense = loader

```tsx
<Suspense fallback={<Loader />}> // ✅
```

***

### ❌ Multiple lazy components need a wrapper

```tsx
<Suspense fallback={<Loader />}>
  <CompA />
  <CompB />
</Suspense>
```

✅ One loader for all

***

## ✅ Interview‑Ready Answer (MEMORIZE)

> **React.lazy does not show a loader by itself.  
> The loader must be provided through `<Suspense fallback={...}>`, which controls where and when the loading UI is displayed.**

***

## ✅ TL;DR

*   ✅ `React.lazy` loads code asynchronously
*   ✅ `<Suspense fallback>` shows loader
*   ❌ No Suspense → error or blank UI
*   ✅ Loader location = Suspense boundary
*   ✅ Used heavily with routes

